</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With jurors deadlocked 11 to 1 for guilt, a mistrial has been declared in the 
case of a former Compton police officer charged with grand theft for allegedly 
cashing the same paycheck twice, prosecutors said this week. 
</P>
<P>
Henry Perez's mistrial was declared by Superior Court Judge George Trammel 
earlier this week after three days of jury deliberations. 
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors intend to retry Perez, 54. A new trial date will be selected at an 
Oct. 22 hearing. 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Dist. Atty. Herb Lapin said Perez twice cashed his $1,200 paycheck on 
March 3, 1989. Perez testified that he was not guilty of the charge. 
</P>
<P>
Lapin said that the one juror who voted for acquittal refused to explain her 
reasons for doing so. 
