</P>
<P>
SOVIETS PLAN REVOLUTION DAY FETE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Communist Party leadership said today that annual Revolution Day 
festivities will go ahead next month, raising the risk of another humiliation 
on Moscow's Red Square for President Mikhail S. Gorbachev. 
</P>
<P>
"Any attempts to deprive our multinational people of its main state celebration 
is illegitimate and unfounded," the Communist Party's secretariat said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
Radical politicians have called for the cancellation of civilian festivities 
Nov. 7 in Moscow and have urged people to channel their efforts instead into 
patching up the city ahead of the harsh winter. At last year's Revolution Day 
parade, about 10,000 Muscovites organized an alternative demonstration during 
which they called on the Communists to surrender their monopoly of power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
