<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHORT TAKES; 
</P>
<P>
ANDREWS SISTER THINKS YOUNG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LINCOLN, Neb. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Maxene Andrews, one-third of the boogie-woogie Andrews Sisters, is singing the 
praises of staying youthful by staying active. 
</P>
<P>
"People say to me, 'When are you going to retire, Maxene?' I say, 'Well, when I 
retire, you'll only know I'm retired when you see them carrying me off the 
stage,' " the 72-year-old singer said this week during a visit to Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
While in Nebraska she will make speeches, including one at a dance to raise 
money for senior centers. 
</P>
<P>
"I love doing these things," Andrews said. "I talk to them (senior citizens) 
about not getting old, if you know what I mean. Just because you've passed that 
mark, you don't have to think that the world is leaving you behind." 
</P>
</TEXT>
